.TH HSH 1 "14 Apr 2026" "0.1" "HSH"
.SH NAME
.B hsh
- command interpreter (simple shell)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./hsh
.SH DESCRIPTION
The hsh shell is a command-line interpreter that provides a command line user interface for Unix-like operating systems.
The shell is both an interactive command language and a scripting language, and is used by the operating system to control the 
execution of the system using shell scripts.

The shell displays a prompt when running in interactive mode and continues to read and execute commands until an exit condition is met.

.SH COMMANDS

__isatty()__ function tests whether fildes,  an  open  file descriptor, is associated with a terminal device.

__getline()__ function is used to read a string or line from an input stream.

__free()__ function is used to free or deallocate dynamically assigned memory and helps in reducing memory wastage.

__strdup()__ function is used to duplicate a string and returns a pointer to a null-terminated byte string. It is useful so that you don't modify the original input on the command line.

__strtok()__ function splits str[] according to given delimiters and returns the next token. It needs to be called in a loop to get all tokens. It returns NULL when there are no more tokens.

__strncmp()__ function compares the first character of two strings. 

__strchr()__ 

__strtol()__

__access()__

__printf()__

__fprintf()__

__sprintf()__

__fork()__

__perror()__

__execve()__

__wait()__

__waitpid()__

__WIFEXITED(status)__

__WEXITSATUS(status)__



The following built-in commands are supported:

.TP
.B exit
Exits the shell. If an argument is provided, it is used as the exit status.
Otherwise, the shell exits with the status of the last executed command.

.TP
.B env
Prints the current environment variables.


.SH PATH RESOLUTION
If a command does not contain a slash (/), the shell searches for it in
the directories specified by the PATH environment variable.

If the command contains a slash, it is treated as a direct path.

.SH RETURN VALUE
The shell returns the exit status of the last executed command.
If a command cannot be found, it returns 127.
If execution fails, it returns 1.

